“

Shipments of smartphones in China are likely to fall to 300m in 2020 after the new pneumonia outbreak, compared with forecasts of 340m-360m before the outbreak.

”

February 13 afternoon, affected by the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Xiaomi 10 series mobile phone live online release, starting price of 3999 yuan. But smartphone shipments in China could fall to 300m in 2020 after the new pneumonia outbreak, according to a previous Xiaomi Management Conference call (compared with previous forecasts of 340m-360m before the outbreak) . It's not just Xiaomi, apple is also affected by the outbreak. A number of new apple products are in the pipeline, but an outbreak of pneumonia could disrupt the company's supply chain, delaying their release, Tianfeng international analyst Ming Guo said in a recent report.

###China is a poor market, with only 3.5 per cent of 5G

Currently, product launches and shipping schedules will be delayed to varying degrees due to plant closures. At the same time, there may be additional operating costs during the outbreak. CEC EXPECTS XIAOMI's smartphone business to struggle to maintain a gross margin of 8-9 per cent.

China's mobile phone market is already challenging. The Chinese smartphone market shipped about 370 million units in 2019, down 7.5 percent from a year earlier, according to IDC. In the same year, Xiaomi shipped 40m handsets, down from 50.8 M in 2018, and its market share fell from 12.8 per cent to 10.9 per cent.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Although Xiaomi is constantly hitting rock bottom prices for 5G handsets, its 5G market share in China is not high. XIAOMI's market share among China's 5G handset makers was only 3.5 percent in 2019, according to IDC.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
###The Indian market is being chased by "sibling brands" 

Global smartphone shipments are also falling, as growth in China is weak. Global smartphone shipments in 2019 were down from the average annual shipments in 2015-2018, according to IDC. But since it shifted its focus overseas, Xiaomi has outperformed globally, with smartphone shipments rising to 125.6 M in 2019 and its global market share rising to 9.2 per cent.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
India, for the second quarter in a row, is Xiaomi's biggest market. Founded in 2014, Xiaomi India overtook Samsung to become the top smartphone seller in India in just over three years. Xiaomi accounted for 28.6 percent of India's mobile phone market in 2019, up 0.3 percentage points from 2018, according to IDC.

But the gap between Xiaomi and other brands is narrowing. Among them, Vivo and Oppo, as "sibling brands" , both showed a faster growth trend. Vivo's market share in India rose from 10.1 percent to 15.6 percent in 2019, while OPPO also rose from 7.2 percent to 10.7 percent, according to IDC.
